[49m[38;5;9m- 130     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m Calibration is the easiest thing to get wrong and the easiest to fix once you notice. The first version of the first system I built had 90% credible intervals that empirically contained 73% of held-out observations, and the calibration backtest revealed it within two weeks. The fix was a hierarchical recalibration on the per-patient random effects; conceptually simple, but the system would have been quietly producing overconfident forecasts for at least a year if we had not built calibration monitoring from day one. The lesson: the calibration backtest is not optional, and it is not something to add later. Build it on day one or you will regret it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Calibration is the easiest thing to get wrong and the easiest to fix once you notice. The first version of the first system I built had 90% credible intervals that empirically contained 73% of held-out observations, and the calibration backtest revealed it within two weeks. The fix was a hierarchical recalibration on the per-patient random effects; conceptually simple, but the system would have been quietly producing overconfident forecasts for at least a year if we had not built calibration monitoring from day one. The lesson: the calibration backtest is not optional, and it is not something to add later. Build it on day one or you will regret it. And build its cousin alongside it: loss-to-follow-up monitoring. The data the model sees is not the data the disease has. Patients who progress fast leave follow-up (they transfer to specialty care, hospitalize, or die), and patients who feel well stop coming in. Both directions of dropout mean the cohort the model trains on silently drifts away from the true disease population over time, and the resulting bias is much harder to detect than a miscalibrated credible interval.
